@NODE Introduction "Introduction"
@TOC Main

      Shellsort is an implementation of one @{"algorythm" LINK Algorythm} in C which is,
  as far I know, best and fastest algorythm for sorting (If anybody
  knows about any better algorythm, let me know). I wrote this program
  because I wanted to have faaaast sort, and I did it. This program is
  about @{B}@{U}9 to 10@{UU}@{UB} times faster than sort we have on Workbench.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Algorythm "Algorythm"
@TOC Main

      Here is sample of algorythm in C source:

void shellsort(char *p[], short n){
	short dist,i,j;
	char  *temp;
	for(dist=n/2;dist>0;dist/=2){
		for(j=i-dist;j>0 && strcmp(p[j],p[j+dist])>0;j-=dist){
			temp=p[j];
			p[j]=p[j+dist];
			p[j+dist]=temp;
		}
	}
}
/* *p[] - text lines, n - number of lines */
@ENDNODE


@NODE Requirements "Requirements and explanations"
@TOC Main

      This program should work on any Amiga with enough memory. Enough
  means folowing: @{I}size of the file to sort@{UI} * 2 + @{I}number of lines
  in the file@{UI} * 5 (in bytes). Why so much? Because I used double buffering
  plus additonal buffer for pointers. This program was @{B}BUILT FOR SPEED@{UB} and
  on the first place for speed. You won't sort files every day, so
  @{I}@{U}when you do it do it fast@{UU}@{UI}. Or if you do sort every day, do it fast anyway.
  Using stdin and stdout will slow down sort and I didn't implement that, and
  wildcards too.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Usage "Using Shellsort"
@TOC Main

      Only possible usage is from CLI.

  > shellsort [@{fg shine}-n@{fg text}] [@{fg shine}-oX@{fg text}] [@{fg shine}-c@{fg text}] <input file> <output file>


      There are three options:

  @{fg shine}-n@{fg text}  This means that any special character(s) at beginning of line (with
      ASCII code less than #32) is (are) ignored and won't be
      in output file. Of course, characters with code greater than 126
      aren't ignored.

  @{fg shine}-oX@{fg text} This option is for sorting with offset X from begining of the line.
      This is on the first place for files that have listings of dirs
      and files, or in other words for files which have lines of same
      length. Of course, you can use it for any purpose.
      @{I}@{U}Warning!@{UU}@{UI}
      Take care when you have files with diferent line lengths and you
      use this option; if offset is greater than length of a line
      then there will be error in sorting, because you jumped entire line
      and get somewhere into the middle of another line.

  @{fg shine}-c@{fg text}  Default is case sensitive sorting. With this option you turn off
      case sensitivity.

  @{B}NOTE!@{UB}  Last line in input file MUST have line feed, or there will be
      some trash at the end of the output file.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Future "In future..."

       This chapter should write the users. I hope there will be
  at least a few people who used my program. If there will be interst
  maybe i'll improve this program. But, remember that if there is more
  options we'll get biger code and slower code.
@ENDNODE


